<section xml:id="relations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Relations</title>
    <p>
        A relation <m>R</m> from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> is a subset of the cartesian product <m>A \times B</m>.
        <me>R \subseteq A \times B</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        Remember a cartesian product is the set of pairs of elements in <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. A relation is any subset of all the possible pairs where the first component belongs to <m>A</m> and the second component belongs to <m>B</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Let's define sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>
        <me>A = \{x,y,z\}</me>
        <me>B = \{1,2,3,4\}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        Lets define a relation from A to B that is a subset of the cart product of
        <me>
            \{x,y,z\} \times \{1,2,3,4\}
        </me>
    </p>
    <p>
        A relation can be any subset. In this example relation, lets say the pairs I am considering are
        <me>
            R = \{(x,2),(y,1),(y,3),(z,2)\}
        </me>
    </p>
    <p>
        We can also express this as
        <me>
            xR2, yR1, yR3, zR2
        </me>
    </p>
    <p>
        This reads <m>X</m> relates to <m>2</m>, <m>y</m> relates to <m>1</m>, etc
    </p>
